{
  "texts": [
    "For example, a company may attempt to trick a spam filter so all emails sent by a competitor are erroneously classified as spam (Shafahi et al., 2018).",
    "Obviously, only influential (malicious) training instances affect a model's prediction.",
    "Some training set attacks rely on influence analysis to craft better (i.e., more influential) poison instances (Fang et al., 2020; Jagielski et al., 2021; Oh et al., 2022).",
    "Since most training set attacks do not assume the adversary knows training's random seed or even necessarily the target model's architecture, poison instances are crafted to maximize their expected group influence (Chen et al., 2017).",
    "Influence and memorization analysis have also been used to improve membership inference attacks, where the adversary attempts to extract sensitive training data provided only a pretrained (language) model (Demontis et al., 2019; Cohen & Giryes, 2022)."
  ]
}